Social Power NBA Dataset

Julia Wilkins & Adrian Naranjo


Data

  • Found on Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/noahgift/social-power-nba
  • Contains combined performance data for players in the 2016-2017 season, and salary, Twitter engagement, and Wikipedia traffic data.


We asked, can we predict…

  1. Salary from performance statistics?
  2. Salary based on social media stats or vice versa?
  3. Team valuations from individual salaries?

Question 1: Can we predict salary from performance statistics?



First, which predictors do we want?

##  [1] "X1"         "Rk"         "PLAYER"     "POSITION.x" "AGE"       
##  [6] "MP"         "FG"         "FGA"        "FG%"        "3P"        
## [11] "3PA"        "3P%"        "2P"         "2PA"        "2P%"       
## [16] "eFG%"       "FT"         "FTA"        "FT%"        "ORB"       
## [21] "DRB"        "TRB"        "AST"        "STL"        "BLK"       
## [26] "TOV"        "PF"         "POINTS"     "TEAM.x"     "GP"        
## [31] "MPG"        "ORPM"       "DRPM"       "RPM"        "WINS_RPM"  
## [36] "PIE"        "PACE"       "W"          "SALARY"


Including all predictors led to issues (hello, collinearity). So, we got rid of some (e.g. Offensive Rebounds) and kept others (e.g. Total Rebounds).

Note: to be precise: we eliminated 18 of the 40 variables



But, we’d still prefer less variables: Best Subset Elimination

No clear consensus.
